[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Yes, it\'s happening. The FDA cleared the first brain computer interface that uses AI in order to enhance cognition. We are in fact using artificial intelligence to expand our own cognitive experience and we\'ll talk about it. This is designed by a company called Nia. It\'s made'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'primarily to work with people who have cognitive deficits such as dementia. If someone is struggling with a task, it will map the brain out automatically using AI and stimulate the parts of the brain that would remember how to do that task. This only works because we have'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'artificial intelligence which can map out the nodes in your brain. Information is not kept in just one spot, although you do have lobes that are specialized. It is diffuse across neurons. Once a circuit is identified, then you can'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'start to access those areas of the brain and reinforce it. And yes, this technology goes a lot farther than that. Brain computer interfaces are no longer a one-way street. Yes, there\'s been BCIs that are supposed to decode language for'

[00:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'someone who say has lost the ability to speak, so it turns their internal monologue into an external monologue. But now we can have information flow back. So yeah, you could actually have say an AI in your head that talks to you and'

[01:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you could stream music. There are a lot of great arguments for expanding our cognition and reaching the next stage of evolution where we really do fuse with our technology and there is an argument that we already have done so. We have'

[01:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all of mankind\'s knowledge at our fingertips. Your brain already believes that your phone is part of your body. We do more in 10 years than we did with 100 or 200 or 300 years ago in the past. Though who\'s to say that fusing with'

[01:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'technology wouldn\'t be a net positive, but we should probably also consider the many abuses that this technology could have. This is, by the way, why states are considering brain privacy laws'

[01:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'before we ever have this technology in the hands of the public. There are a number of consumer products which allow you to read your own EEG data and that could be used for things like health and wellness, but it could also be utilized for advertisement. How you respond to'

[01:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something could be used in order to sell you things. There is the concern if you had a brain computer interface that it could be hacked, that it could be used to encourage you to do things. And that is going to be an entirely new area of'

[02:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'law that will be fascinating and also terrifying. Because yes, the technology exists to use a brain computer interface to send messages and also influence actions. Imagine having this technology and'

[02:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'coming up with the thought and not being entirely sure where that thought came from. Incidentally, this technology could also be used to steal ideas and not compensate them for them. I could see a world where it says in the fine print that your ideas belong to the BCI'

[02:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that\'s scanning your brain. Hopefully not, because it does seem that lawmakers are thinking ahead prior to this technology hitting the public. Because yes, researchers have been able to implant false memories into mice and'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they\'re working on episodic memories because all of your neurons follow a pattern. We can see a memory moving through your brain and that can also be deleted. That might be a treatment for PTSD and I am still deciding how I feel'

[02:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'about that. Aside from the spookier aspects of all of this, I am genuinely excited for a lot of the treatments that are coming out of this. We could have treatments for things like Parkinson\'s or dementia or even cerebral palsy. You can utilize'

[03:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'neural pathways and stimulate them in order to bypass damaged ones. I really do think that stem cell transplants are going to be a much better treatment for Parkinson\'s, but yes, neural stimulation is also'

[03:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something that has been tried and is quite promising. There is a darker side to all of this and it\'s one that I don\'t think we talk about enough and that\'s what happens when this technology becomes obsolete. Because at the speed'

[03:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that we\'re moving, there\'s no guarantee that this tech will be maintained and we already see that. We\'ve seen people with bionic eyes end up losing their vision because the company went out of business. We\'ve seen people lose their'

[03:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'medical devices because it is a liability to continue to maintain it after the trial has been completed. A lot of this technology is proprietary, so it may not even be safe to remove it if somebody doesn\'t force you to do so.'

[04:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We are no longer talking about a situation where your grandparent doesn\'t know how to use email and haha, that\'s funny. We\'re talking about a situation where your parent or older siblings brain chip could already be obsolete and'

[04:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they need to pay for a new one. Or maybe you get a free one because you need to have a brain chip to participate in society not unlike cell phones except the one that you got comes with tons of advertisements. These might sound like'

[04:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'absurd ideas, but they\'re really not all that far off. I got to say I\'ve been someone who\'s been desperately against getting brain chips, if anything because you risk brain damage having it inserted and if it fails, you risk brain damage'

[04:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'having it removed. It could do things like leak battery acid into your brain. The technology is not at the point of being safe. However, the idea of improving cognition or even helping to treat ADHD, which is a really big'

[04:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'problem for me and causes me lots of issues in my everyday life. Yeah, that is kind of appealing. All of the other ethical and really dystopian risks like having your brain chip hacked make me hesitant to say that I would actually do'

[05:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it. Perhaps if it was non-invasive and really demonstrated itself to be safe, I would be willing to give it a try. However, we are not at that point, but that\'s never stopped people before. I hope you\'ve enjoyed this. If you want a'

